# NETSTACK — Interactive Computer Networks Learning Platform

A beginner-friendly, hands-on educational platform for learning computer networking fundamentals through interactive simulations and visualizations.

## 🌐 Live Demo
[View NETSTACK](https://netstack.example.com) — Start learning networks today!

## Features

### 📚 8 Interactive Modules
- **Foundations**: OSI Model, TCP/IP Model, Network Topologies
- **Addressing & Delivery**: IP Addressing & Subnets, Switching (Layer 2), Routing (Layer 3)
- **Transport & Apps**: TCP vs UDP, DNS & HTTP
- **Interactive Lab**: Build custom network topologies with drag-and-drop

### 🎨 Network Lab (Interactive Simulator)
Build real-world network topologies with:
- **15 Network Devices**: PCs, Servers, Routers, Switches, Firewalls, Load Balancers, DNS/DHCP servers, and more
- **4 Cable Types**:
  - 🔌 Ethernet (1 Gbps, 0.1 ms latency)
  - 💡 Fiber Optic (100 Gbps, 0.002 ms latency)
  - 📶 Wireless WiFi (300 Mbps, 1-5 ms latency)
  - ⚡ Power cables
- **Smart Connection Validation**: Only compatible devices can connect
- **Visual Cable Properties**: Hover to see speed and latency specs
- **Drag & Drop Canvas**: Intuitive network building interface
- **Real-time Statistics**: Track devices and connections

### 🔧 Technology Stack
- **HTML5** — Semantic markup
- **CSS3** — Modern design tokens, responsive layouts
- **Vanilla JavaScript** — No dependencies, lightweight (~3KB total)
- **SVG** — Smooth path animations for packet visualization

### 🎯 Design Philosophy
- Zero prerequisites required
- Learn by building, not reading
- Visual, hands-on approach to complex concepts
- Professional networking UI inspired by router/switch LEDs
- Accessibility-first (reduced motion support, semantic HTML)

## Project Structure
```
netsite/
├── index.html              # Home page & introduction
├── osi-model.html         # OSI 7-layer model
├── tcpip-model.html       # TCP/IP model
├── topologies.html        # Network topologies
├── ip-addressing.html     # IP & subnetting
├── switching.html         # Layer 2 switching
├── routing.html           # Layer 3 routing
├── tcp-udp.html          # Transport layer protocols
├── dns-http.html         # Application layer services
├── network-lab.html      # Interactive lab & simulator
├── css/
│   └── style.css         # Design system & components
├── js/
│   ├── nav.js            # Navigation & sidebar
│   └── main.js           # Core animations
└── Readme                # This file
```

## Color System
- 🔵 **Cyan** (#4cc9f0) — Data in flight, active states
- 🟢 **Green** (#3ddc84) — Link up, success, ACK
- 🟡 **Amber** (#f5a623) — Warnings, collisions, retransmit
- 🔴 **Red** (#ef4444) — Link down, dropped packets
- 🟣 **Violet** (#8b7cf6) — Headers, secondary emphasis

## Getting Started

### View Locally
```bash
cd netsite
python -m http.server 8000
# Open http://localhost:8000
```

### Build a Network
1. Go to **Network Lab** section
2. Drag devices from the left palette onto the canvas
3. Click **Connect** button and select two devices
4. Choose compatible cable type from popup
5. Hover over cables to see performance specs

